<seg id=1> A 25-Floor High Building in Detroit Blasted into Ashes within 30 Seconds </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (FNA news from Detroit)The Hardson Plaza with 107 years history was blasted into ashes within 30 seconds the day before yesterday. </seg>
<seg id=3> This 25-floor steel reinforced concrete plaza is the highest building which was exploded by plastic explosive at fixed points. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The Hardson Plaza used to be the largest retail shop in the world, and the ground symbol of Detroit as well. </seg>
<seg id=5> It turned into 360 million tons of debris in the sound of the explosion of  1,215 kg plastic explosive. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> At 5:45 p.m. local time, the Hardson Plaza began a series of inner-oriented explosion, heavey dust mass engulfing the surrounding people. </seg>
<seg id=7> A citizen said he didn't expect to be blackened by the dust. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> A few outsiders broke into shouts of joy when the Plaza collapsed, but some others weeped, for they would never see the familiar building. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> During the 1950s', the Plaza experienced its time of great prosperity with nearly 100,000 visitors a day </seg>
<seg id=10> including some famous stars that time such as Garbal and Park. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Mr. Archer, Mayor of Detroit, told the public that the authority was willing to provide the opportunity of operating the exploder to the public, in order to raise 150,000 US dollars cherity donation. </seg>
<seg id=12> But because the Plaza used to the pride of Detroit, no one would like to operate the exploder and destroy this building. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> A man who insisted proctection of the building said that it was sad. </seg>
</p>
